%md
## Welcome to Zeppelin.
##### This is a live tutorial, you can run the code yourself. (Shift-Enter to Run)

msg.data:
Welcome to Zeppelin.

This is a live tutorial, you can run the code yourself. (Shift-Enter to Run)

paragraphs.text:
%md
#### 1. Clone a tutorial repository.

The repository includes a tool for generating sample data and a notebook for tutorial.

msg.data:
1. Clone a tutorial repository.

The repository includes a tool for generating sample data and a notebook for tutorial.

paragraphs.text:
%sh
cd ~/
git clone https://github.com/mnms/tutorials.git

%md
#### 2. Generate sample data

You can find various options of generator in this [page](https://github.com/mnms/tutorials/tree/master/prep-sample-data#options).
Now, generate 24 csv files in /nvme/data_01/loadData. Each file has 2,296,622 rows.

msg.data:
2. Generate sample data

You can find various options of generator in this page.
Now, generate 24 csv files in /nvme/data_01/loadData. Each file has 2,296,622 rows.

paragraphs.text:
%sh
cd ~/tutorials/prep-sample-data
python3 prep.py --outdir /nvme/data_01/loadData

msg.data:
* generating sample data...
* 24 files generated.

paragraphs.text:
%md
#### 3. Create a temporary view of CSV data

Load CSV data, and create a temporary view. This view will be used to insert into a table of LightningDB.

msg.data:
3. Create a temporary view of CSV data

Load CSV data, and create a temporary view. This view will be used to insert into a table of LightningDB.

paragraphs.text:
%spark
val csvDf = spark.sqlContext.read
    .format("csv")
    .option("header", "true")
    .option("inferSchema", "true")
    .load("file:///nvme/data_01/loadData")

csvDf.createOrReplaceTempView("CSV_DATA")

msg.data: csvDf: org.apache.spark.sql.DataFrame = [event_time: bigint, name: string ... 6 more fields]

paragraphs.text:
%md
#### 4. Table schema of CSV data

CSV data include event_time, name, sur_name, sex, city, latitude, longitude and country.
The latitude and longitude are the coordinate of the city.

The latitude and longitude are the coordinate of the city.

paragraphs.text:
%md
#### 5. Create Table of LightningDB

The name of data source is "r2", which means "redis + rockdb".
The data source has various options, and you can check it in [this page](https://mnms.github.io/docs/data-ingestion-and-querying/)
The columns of EVENT_TIME and CITY are used as partition column. The partitions columns are important for performance because they are not only norms for distributing data during ingestion, but keys of filtering data during querying.

msg.data:
5. Create Table of LightningDB

The name of data source is “r2”, which means “redis + rockdb”.
The data source has various options, and you can check it in this page
The columns of EVENT_TIME and CITY are used as partition column. The partitions columns are important for performance because they are not only norms for distributing data during ingestion, but keys of filtering data during querying.

paragraphs.text:
%spark
spark.sql("""CREATE OR REPLACE TEMPORARY VIEW LIGHTNING_TUTORIAL
            |(EVENT_TIME STRING, NAME STRING, SUR_NAME STRING, SEX STRING, CITY STRING, LATITUDE DOUBLE, LONGITUDE DOUBLE, COUNTRY STRING)
            |USING r2
            |OPTIONS (table '100', host '127.0.0.1', port '18100', partitions 'EVENT_TIME CITY', mode 'nvkvs', rowstore 'true', at_least_one_partition_enabled 'no')""".stripMargin).show()

%md
#### 6. Insert CSV data into LightningDB.

Insert CSV data into LightningDB.

msg.data:
6. Insert CSV data into LightningDB.

Insert CSV data into LightningDB.

paragraphs.text:
%spark
spark.sql("INSERT INTO LIGHTNING_TUTORIAL SELECT * FROM CSV_DATA").show

%md
#### 7. Querying data from LightningDB.

Now, you can query data from LightningDB.
Each redis node of LightningDB is assigned to a single Spark partition.

%md
#### 8. Clear data from LightningDB

You can clear data from LightningDB by reseting cluster of LightningDB.

msg.data:
8. Clear data from LightningDB

You can clear data from LightningDB by reseting cluster of LightningDB.

paragraphs.text:
%sh
echo "cluster restart --reset" | fbctl
